cards.abstract: Will NATO’s new deal with Ukraine draw American troops into the war?

slides.title: The answer is almost certainly not
slides.body: On July 7th, NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced a new assistance package for Ukraine that will see the embattled country receive years of support from the alliance in a pre-summit conference ahead of the military bloc's July 12th meeting.

image.title: The answer is almost certainly not
image.caption: On July 7th, NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced a new assistance package for Ukraine that will see the embattled country receive years of support from the alliance in a pre-summit conference ahead of the military bloc's July 12th meeting.

slides.title: Ukraine’s future NATO membership
slides.body: Heads of State and Government from across the military alliance are set to gather for a historic summit on the future path of transatlantic security and the issue at the top of the list for the military bloc’s members will be the issue of Ukraine’s future membership.

slides.body: The summit is set to take place in Vilnius, Lithuania, and ahead of the historic meeting, Stoltenberg held a pre-summit conference announcing the details behind a three-point program that he was sure the alliance’s leaders would agree on once at the summit.

subCards.title: Musk says Twitter has lost half its advertising revenue
subCards.abstract: NEW YORK: Twitter owner Elon Musk said Saturday that the social media platform he bought for $44 billion last October has lost roughly half of its advertising revenue. "We're still negative cash flow, due to ~50% drop in advertising revenue plus heavy debt load," the billionaire said in a post, responding to a user who was giving suggestions on financing for the platform. "Need to reach positive cash flow before we have the luxury of anything...

subCards.title: UK formally signs up to trans-Pacific trading bloc
subCards.abstract: London: The UK government on Sunday announced it had formally signed a treaty to join a major Indo-Pacific bloc, as it looks beyond Europe for trading opportunities post-Brexit. Business and Trade Secretary Kemi Badenoch signed the accession protocol for the Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership (CPTPP) in New Zealand. It makes the United Kingdom the first new member and first European nation to join the bloc...

subCards.title: Never rub your eyes! 15 risks you take when you do!
subCards.abstract: Never rub your eyes! 15 risks you take when you do!

slides.title: A common habit that has more dangers than you might think!
slides.body: Rubbing your eyes might feel totally normal and harmless when you're trying to get rid of an uncomfortable feeling or you are tired. But here's the thing: it can actually mess up your eye health big time, especially if you go at it too forcefully or way too often. Keep reading to find out why you gotta ditch this habit once and for all.

image.title: A common habit that has more dangers than you might think!
image.caption: Rubbing your eyes might feel totally normal and harmless when you're trying to get rid of an uncomfortable feeling or you are tired. But here's the thing: it can actually mess up your eye health big time, especially if you go at it too forcefully or way too often. Keep reading to find out why you gotta ditch this habit once and for all.

slides.title: Cornea scratches
slides.body:
According to the Cleveland Clinic, eye rubbing can cause micro-scratches on the cornea that can lead to serious damage, including scar tissue and permanent vision problems.

Photo: Dominika Gregušová / Pexels

image.title: Cornea scratches
image.caption:
According to the Cleveland Clinic, eye rubbing can cause micro-scratches on the cornea that can lead to serious damage, including scar tissue and permanent vision problems.

Photo: Dominika Gregušová / Pexels

slides.title: Keratoconus: A risky consequence
slides.body:
The Atlantic Eye Institute warns that excessive eye rubbing can lead to keratoconus, a condition where the cornea becomes thin and changes shape, causing blurry, distorted vision.

Image: Madhero88 / Wikimedia

subCards.abstract: Fran Drescher and the cast of 'The Nanny': Where are they now?

slides.title: The cult sitcom of the 90s
slides.body: In November 2023, it's 30 years since the first episode of 'The Nanny' aired. Many of us remember the quirkiness of nanny Fran Fine, who suddenly arrived and wreaked havoc in the haughty and elegant Sheffield family home.

image.title: The cult sitcom of the 90s
image.caption: In November 2023, it's 30 years since the first episode of 'The Nanny' aired. Many of us remember the quirkiness of nanny Fran Fine, who suddenly arrived and wreaked havoc in the haughty and elegant Sheffield family home.

slides.title: What happened to the actors and actresses of 'The Nanny'?
slides.body: Sometimes, the actors and actresses of a cult TV series never duplicate the success they had with the show. But that doesn't mean we forget about them! Let's check out what happened to the cast and how they are today... after three decades.

image.title: What happened to the actors and actresses of 'The Nanny'?
image.caption: Sometimes, the actors and actresses of a cult TV series never duplicate the success they had with the show. But that doesn't mean we forget about them! Let's check out what happened to the cast and how they are today... after three decades.

slides.title: Frances Fine
slides.body: Let's start with her, the absolute protagonist of 'The Nanny'. From 1993 to 1999, she kept us company with her irony and joy: Fran Fine, a Jewish woman from New York. Let's find out what happened to her.

cards.title: The Blade Runner's Rise and Ruin: The downfall of Oscar Pistorius
cards.abstract: The Blade Runner's Rise and Ruin: The downfall of Oscar Pistorius

slides.title: A unique athlete
slides.body: Oscar Pistorius became famous when he became the first athlete with double amputated legs to participate in the Olympic Games (London 2012). He is the only Olympic and Paralympic athlete in history, an achievement that would eventually be overshadowed by the gruesome murder of his girlfriend.

image.title: A unique athlete
image.caption: Oscar Pistorius became famous when he became the first athlete with double amputated legs to participate in the Olympic Games (London 2012). He is the only Olympic and Paralympic athlete in history, an achievement that would eventually be overshadowed by the gruesome murder of his girlfriend.

slides.title: Fibular hemimelia
slides.body: Pistorius was born with fibrous hemimelia, a condition that left him missing a fibula in both legs. When he was just eleven months old, both legs were amputated below the knees.

image.title: Fibular hemimelia
image.caption: Pistorius was born with fibrous hemimelia, a condition that left him missing a fibula in both legs. When he was just eleven months old, both legs were amputated below the knees.

slides.title: Success in sport without two legs
slides.body: But the fact that his legs were amputated did not stop him from playing all kinds of sports with the help of prostheses. He played water polo, tennis and rugby, where he suffered a serious knee injury that led him to take up running, while working on his recovery.
